05419nam a22008415i 9781442683389DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162001onc    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013938219  a97814426833897 a10.3138/97814426833892doi  a(DE-B1597)465115  a(OCoLC)944177228  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aHQ778.7.E85bJ46 2001 7aSOC0250002bisacsh04a362.71/2/09422100aWho Cares? :bWomen's Work, Childcare, and Welfare State Redesign /ced. by Jane Jenson, Mariette Sineau. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2016] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (416 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Comparative Political Economy and Public Policy00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. The Care Dimension in Welfare State Redesign -- t2. New Contexts, New Policies -- t3. Belgium: The Vices and Virtues of Pragmatism -- t4. France: Reconciling Republican Equality with 'Freedom of Choice' -- t5. Italy: Policy without Participation -- t6. Sweden: Models in Crisis -- t7. Europe: An Actor without a Role -- t8. Comparing Childcare Programs: Commonalities Amid Variety -- t9. Citizenship in the Era of Welfare State Redesign -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBy focusing on childcare and systematically comparing national experiences in Belgium, France, Italy, Sweden, and the European Union, Who Cares? provides detailed information on recent social policies and a clear perspective on welfare state redesign. Many countries have now designed childcare policies to reconcile family and work. Some encourage parents to provide their own childcare by granting parental leave; others encourage parents to stay at work by supporting childcare services. Using the case of childcare policy, the contributors to this volume examine how public policy choices over the last three decades have been fashioned by specific understandings of the gendered division of labour.The authors of the country studies analyse specific childcare strategies and place them within the larger context of state approaches to women's roles. They argue that an examination of the direction and the form of social spending, in this period when such spending is under attack, contributes to our understanding of new principles of citizenship as they have been developed and articulated by governments.Who Cares? highlights the connection between childcare and employment, and makes a significant contribution to the literature on citizenship and women's work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aChild carexGovernment policyzEurope. 0aMothersxEmploymentzEurope. 0aWork and familyxGovernment policyzEurope. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Work.2bisacsh1 aBimbi, Franca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaune-Richard, Anne-Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJenson, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJenson, Jane, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMahon, Rianne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarques-Pereira, Bérengère, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaye, Olivier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoss, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSineau, Mariette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSineau, Mariette, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSola, Vincent Delia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook pack